    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Early 20th-century eugenicists primarily relied on pseudo-scientific theories to justify racial hierarchies. They argued that certain racial groups, particularly those with lighter skin and European ancestry, possessed superior intelligence, moral character, and physical abilities, making them more \"fit\" for society. In contrast, darker-skinned and non-European groups were deemed \"inferior\" due to their alleged lower intelligence, moral decay, and physical weaknesses. They also claimed that intermarriage between these groups would lead to the \"degeneration\" of the \"inferior\" partner, reinforcing the notion of racial purity.",
