      "content": "Eugenicists used cranial measurements to argue that the \"Caucasian\" skull was more \"refined\" and \"adaptable\" than other racial groups. They claimed that a longer and more narrow skull indicated higher intelligence, while a shorter and broader skull was associated with lower intelligence and \"savage\" tendencies. They also used the concept of \"brachycephaly\" (short, broad skull) to describe non-European groups, implying that they were less intelligent and more prone to violence. In terms of IQ, eugenicists often cited studies that claimed to show a correlation between cranial capacity and intelligence, such as the work of William Stern, who supposedly found that IQ scores were directly proportional to cranial capacity. They used these metrics to justify the idea that European-Americans were more \"civilized\" and \"advanced\" than other racial groups, and that intermarriage between these groups would lead to the \"degeneration\" of the \"inferior\" partner.",
